# Read in all the libraries and data
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import os
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

os.chdir('/Users/ashapereira/Downloads')
county_data = pd.read_csv("project_477_777.csv", index_col="Row.Label")
county_data = pd.DataFrame(county_data)

Introduction¶

  • For this project, I chose to examine the outcome Poor Health, which represents the proportion of county that has a poor health status. I examined different demographic and social determinants of health at the county level in order to draw insights and comparisons between different characteristics. I chose to focus deeply on the interplay between Poor Health and Physical Inactivity in order to see their correlation and their relative association with similar factors such as adult obesity, food insecurity, proportion of smokers, and excessive drinkers. As someone who enjoys working out and eating healthy, I am interested to see the impact of physical inactivity on health outcomes and how it correlates with other factors in different counties in the US.

Questions of Interest¶

  1. How are poor health outcomes and physical inactivity related and how does this association change over food insecurity quartile?
  1. How do other related factors like adult obesity, food insecurity, proportion of smokers, and excessive drinking relate to poor health outcomes, and how does their impact change when related to physical inactivity?
  1. What do combined models reveal about poor health outcomes?

  • First, I examined a summary of the dataset and the y variable Poor Health. I printed the dimensions of the dataset as well as the data types in order to gain an understanding of the data I am working with.
  • I also examined the summary statistics of Poor Health. Notably, its mean value is .174 and its median value is .167. Since these values are close but the mean is greater, I wanted to investigate if the poor health distribution is right skewed. To do so, I plotted the distribution plot and saw that the distribution of poor health was skewed to the right, indicating that there are some counties with higher proportions of poor health that drags the distribution to the right.
  • Next, I examined my other main variable of interest, Physical Inactivity. This value represents the proportion of population that is physically inactive. In the summary statistics, its mean and median is .256, which indicates that the distribution will be centrally distributed. After examining the distribution plot, this assumption is true.

  • Then, I looked at health by state to draw conclusions about different health outcomes on a statewise basis. I found the top and bottom states by mean health outcome and evaluated its differences between the mean physical inactivity outcome.
  • The states with the largest proportion of poor health were Arkansas, Alabama, West Virginia, Mississippi, and Kentucky. Similarly, the states with the largest proportion of physical inactivity were Arkansas, Mississippi, Oklahoma, Kentucky, and Louisiana. The common states from both lists include Arkansas, Mississippi, and Kentucky, which indicates that there may be a correlation between physical inactivity and poor health outcomes, which makes a lot of sense. These states are all in the south, indicating there may be a regional relationship to both health and physical inactivity.
  • There is also not a great difference between the means of the top 5 and the means of the bottom 5, indicating that there is a small range that the poor health outcomes fall between (.11-.23) and the physical inactivity proportions (.16-.33).
  • The states with the smallest proportion of poor health were Minnesota, Rhode Island, South Dakota, Vermont, and Connecticut. The states with the smallest proportion of physical inactivity were California, Utah, Oregon, DC, and Colorado. Interestingly enough, there seems to not be a similar correlation with the healthier states since there are no common states in each list. Additionally, the majority of states with a low amount of physical inactivity are on the West Coast, indicating that that region may be more inclined to exercise (perhaps due to nicer weather?)
  • Next, I plotted box plots by state and by poor health and physical inactivity. It is interesting to see how the distributions for each state vary, indicating that some states with longer tails and more outliers may have larger ranges that their outcomes fall into. An example of this for health outcomes is Texas, which has a long tail and many outliers towards a higher proportion of poor health outcomes. An example for physical inactivity is Florida, which has a long tail towards a high proportion of physical inactivity, perhaps owing to the larger population of old people in Florida who may not be as active.
  • Finally, I created a jointplot to map how poor health follows physical inactivity. There looks to be a positive correlation between the two, but variation is high.

insec_health_phys_res = insec_health_phys.fit()
print(insec_health_phys_res.summary())

  • Next, I wanted to introduce another variable and examine the relationship between physical inactivity and food insecurity. I chose food insecurity because I hypothesized that those who were in Q5, or had the highest level of food insecurity, would most likely be physically inactive due to not having enough energy to work out.
  • I then plotted physical inactivity by the y variable poor health and categorized by food insecurity. There was a lot of variability, so it was difficult to ascertain correct findings from this plot. However, it is clear that those in Q5 for food insecurity had the highest rates of poor health at different levels of food insecurity. A similar finding follows for the rest of the quintiles, with Q1 having the lowest rates of poor health for a given level of physical inactivity.
  • I then ran three different regressions to see the different associations between each of the variables. For the first regression, I just ran physical inactivity as a predictor variable. For the second, I ran physical inactivity and food insecurity quintile as predictor variables. Finally, I ran physical inactivity and food insecurity quintile as well as their interaction as predictor variables to see the effect of physical inactivity on the value of another food insecurity quintile.
  • For the first model, the R squared value of .364 indicates that physical inactivity does not strongly explain the variability in poor health. The p value is 0, indicating that physical inactivity is a significant predictor of poor health.
  • For the second model, the R squared value of .522 indicates that physical inactivity and food insecurity moderately explains the variability in poor health. The p value is 0 for all quantiles except for Q2, indicating that physical inactivity and all other quantiles are significant predictors of poor health.
  • For the third model, the R squared value of .528 indicates that physical inactivity, food insecurity, and their interaction moderately explains the variability in poor health. Interestingly, nearly all of the predictors became insignificant when the interaction model was introduced, other than physical inactivity and the interaction between physical inactivity and Q5 food insecurity, indicating that we cannot draw conclusions about the other quartiles and their interactions with physical inactivity since their p values were greater than .05.

  • I then wanted to introduce another variable and examine the relationship between physical inactivity and adult obesity. I chose adult obesity because it logically follows that obesity follows from physical inactivity.
  • Then, I plotted the relationships between adult obesity and poor health as well as physical inactivity and adult obesity. Although there was a lot of variability in points, there was a general positive relationship between adult obesity and poor health as well as physical inactivity and adult obesity.
  • I then ran three different regressions to see the different associations between each of the variables. For the first regression, I just ran adult obestity as a predictor variable. For the second, I ran physical inactivity and adult obesity as predictor variables. Finally, I ran physical inactivity and adult obesity as well as their interaction as predictor variables to see the effect of physical inactivity on the value of another adult obesity.

  • For the second model, the R squared value of .367 indicates that physical inactivity and adult obesity does not strongly explain the variability in poor health. The p value is 0, indicating that physical inactivity and adult obesity are significant predictors of poor health.
  • For the third model, the R squared value of .388 indicates that physical inactivity, adult obesity, and their interaction does not strongly explain the variability in poor health. All of the predictors are significant when the interaction model was introduced, since their p values were less than .05.

  • I then wanted to introduce another variable and examine the relationship between physical inactivity and proportion of smokers. I chose proportion of smokers because smoking has been shown to harm your lungs, which could impair the ability to be physically active.

All of the predictors are significant when the interaction model was introduced, since their p values were less than .05 except for proportion of smokers, which means that it is not a significant variable when the interaction term is present.

Again, there was a lot of variability in points, but a general neutral relationship between percentage rural and poor health. There was a general positive relationship between physical inactivity and percentage rural.
  • I then ran three different regressions to see the different associations between each of the variables. For the first regression, I just ran percentage rural as a predictor variable. For the second, I ran physical inactivity and percentage rural as predictor variables. Finally, I ran physical inactivity and percentage rural as well as their interaction as predictor variables to see the effect of physical inactivity on the value of percentage rural.
  • For the first model, the R squared value of .015 indicates that percentage rural does not at all strongly explain the variability in poor health. The p value is less than .05, indicating that percentage rural is a significant predictor of poor health.
  • For the second model, the R squared value of .375 indicates that physical inactivity and percentage rural does not strongly explain the variability in poor health. The p value is less than .05, indicating that physical inactivity and percentage rural are significant predictors of poor health.
  • For the third model, the R squared value of .378 indicates that physical inactivity, percentage rural, and their interaction moderately explains the variability in poor health. All of the predictors are significant when the interaction model was introduced, since their p values were less than .05. Again, the model becomes stronger when the interaction term is introduced, causing the R squared value to increase slightly.

Decision Tree¶

In [30]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn import tree
import sklearn

Xcts = county_data[["Physical.Inactivity", "Excessive.Drinking", 
                    "Proportion.of.Smokers", "Adult.Obesity","Percent.Rural","Percent.Females"]]
Xcts = pd.DataFrame(data=Xcts)

Xcat = county_data[["Food.Insecurity.Quintile"]]
Xcat = pd.DataFrame(data=Xcat)

Xcat_dum = pd.get_dummies(Xcat)

X = pd.merge(Xcts, Xcat_dum,left_index=True,right_index=True)
y = county_data["Poor.Health"]

# Create the train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.4, random_state=1940) 

regtree = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=0, max_leaf_nodes=7)
regtree.fit(X_train, y_train)

fig = plt.figure(num=None, figsize=(12, 9), dpi=80, facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
tree.plot_tree(regtree, filled=True, feature_names=X.columns);
pass
  • To round out my analysis, I created a decision tree using the variables Physical.Inactivity, Excessive.Drinking, Proportion.of.Smokers, Adult.Obesity, Percent.Rural, and Percent.Females.
  • I chose to limit the nodes in the tree to 7 to preserve readability and comprehension.
  • The key variables in the tree are proportion of smokers, excessive drinking, and food insecurity quintile. This makes sense, since each of these variables had significant predictors for Poor Health.
  • In this case, the largest value was .234, which was found when proportion of smokers was greater than .193, and when excessive drinking was less than or equal to .151. In this bucket, there are 264 samples. Another high value was .216, which occured when proportion of smokers was greater than .193, excessive drinking was greater than .151, and food insecurity quintile was Q5. This makes sense with our earlier analysis, showing that being in Q5 and having a high proportion of smokers leads to poor health outcomes at a greater frequency.
  • For the best health, these are the ones with the lowest value for poor health outcomes, which is .132. These are when proportion of smoking is below or equal to .156 and excessive drinking is above .17. This follows the trend from before where low proportion of smoking correlates with better health outcomes, but more excessive drinking actually correlates with better health outcomes as well.

Cost Complexity Pruning¶

In [41]:
dtr = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=1940)
path = dtr.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities


rgrs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas: 
    dtr = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=1940, max_leaf_nodes=6,ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha,max_depth=4)
    dtr.fit(X_train, y_train)
    rgrs.append(dtr)

train_scores = [dtr.score(X_train, y_train) for dtr in rgrs]
test_scores = [dtr.score(X_test, y_test) for dtr in rgrs]


best = pd.Series(test_scores).idxmax()

print(test_scores[best])
best_tree = rgrs[best]

fig2 = plt.figure(num=None, figsize=(12, 12), facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
tree.plot_tree(best_tree, filled=True, fontsize=10,feature_names=X.columns);
pass

0.5752011115513878
  • Next, I did cost-complexity pruning to mitigate the effect of over or under fitting. I wanted to remove the weakest link in the tree, creating a tree to explore for the best generalizability.
  • However, this tree ended up being very similar to the original decision tree that was generated. This could mean that the original data did not suffer from over or underfitting to the model. I set the max leaf nodes to 6 for readability again.
  • Then, I printed the best tree as well as the test score at best. The r squared value for the tree was .575, which is one of the higher values that we have observed throughout the project.

Conclusions¶

  • Q1: How are poor health outcomes and physical inactivity related and how does this association change over food insecurity quartile?

    • Overall, I saw that physical inactivity was positively related to poor health outcomes. Although there was variability in the graphs, there was a general positive trend in the regression plots. However, when comparing the two in a regression output, the R squared value of .364 indicates that physical inactivity does not strongly explain the variability in poor health. Its p value is 0, indicating that physical inactivity is a significant predictor of poor health.

    • When adding the additional dimension of food insecurity quantile, it is clear that those in Q5 for food insecurity had the highest rates of poor health at different levels of food insecurity. A similar finding follows for the rest of the quintiles, with Q1 having the lowest rates of poor health for a given level of physical inactivity. My hypothesis that those in Q5 with the highest level of food insecurity would most likely be physically inactive due to not having enough energy to work out was corroborated by the data.

  • Q2: How do other related factors like adult obesity, food insecurity, proportion of smokers, and excessive drinking relate to poor health outcomes, and how does their impact change when related to physical inactivity?

    • From analyzing other factors, the majority of my hypotheses were correct-- as adult obesity, food insecurity, and proportion of smokers increases, poor health outcomes increases. These factors all also had a positive correlation with physical inactivity. The one factor that had a different relationship was excessive drinking-- although I thought that it would positively correlated with poor health and physical inactivity, it actually has a negative relationship with both. I also looked at certain demographic features to see their relationships, such as percent of females and percent rural. For percent of females, there was only a neutral relationship and percentage female was not a significant predictor of poor health. However, for percent rural, there was a general neutral relationship between percentage rural and poor health. There was a general positive relationship between physical inactivity and percentage rural. This is surprising due to physical inactivity and poor health being positively related as shown in question 1.

  • Q3: What do combined models reveal about poor health outcomes?

    • The combined models were a useful tool to review the relationships between selected x-variables as well as their impact on poor health. From the pairplot, we saw the pairwise relationships between the variables. Overall, the general positive relationships included poor health and physical inactivity. Proportion of smokers and poor health, physical inactivity. Adult obesity and poor health, physical inactivity, and proportion of smokers. The general negative relationships include: excessive drinking and all other factors. Then examining the decision tree, we found that the key variables in the tree are proportion of smokers, excessive drinking, and food insecurity quintile. We found the bucket that contained the metrics for the best health (low proportion of smoking, moderate excessive drinking) and the one that contained the metrics for the worst health outcomes (high proportion of smoking, low excessive drinking, food insecurity quartile 5). The cost complexity pruning of this tree confirmed that it was not over or underfit and that these variables are indeed important.

Suggestions for further research¶

  1. First, I would find more data on the relationship between excessive drinking and diet. I was surprised by the result in the data that there was not a positive correlation between excessive drinking and poor health outcomes. I would like to get more data on drinking habits and nutrition on the county level to explore this issue more.
  2. Next, I would be interested in verifying results for new time periods. Then, I could employ a longitudinal study to see if poor health outcomes change over time and how fluctuating physical inactivity is similarly altered. It would also be interesting to do a pre COVID and current time period analysis to see if COVID improved or hurt physical inactivity and its impact on poor health outcomes.
  3. Finally, I would be interested in segmenting the data deeper by age, to see if younger or older age brackets have different outcomes. For states like Florida, I noticed in my analysis some outliers, so I would be interested in seeing if that was due to Florida having an older state population.
